> One of the most underrated childhood comfort foods, in our opinion? The humble sloppy Joe. Adults and kids alike will love this version, which has a few flavor upgrades to take it to the next level.

Wash and dry all produce.

Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2%units}, separating whites from greens. Zest and quarter @lime{1%unit}. Drain @pineapple{4%ounce} over a #small bowl{}, reserving juice.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add @ground pork{10%ounce} and a big pinch of @salt{}; cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned, ~{3-5%minutes} (it'll finish cooking in step 5).

> TIP: If there's excess grease in your pan, carefully pour it out.

Meanwhile, in a #medium bowl{}, thoroughly combine @shredded red cabbage{4%ounce}, scallion greens, @mayonnaise{2%tbsp}, lime zest, 1 TBSP reserved pineapple juice (2 TBSP for 4 servings), and a big squeeze of lime juice. Season generously with salt and @pepper{}.

Halve @potato buns{2%units}; toast if desired.

Add scallion whites, @sweet and smoky BBQ seasoning{1%tbsp}, and @chipotle powder{¼%tsp} (add more if you like things spicy) to pan with pork. Cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Add pineapple, @ketchup{4%tbsp}, @beef stock concentrate{1%unit}, half the @cornstarch{1%tbsp}, remaining reserved pineapple juice, 1⁄3 cup water (½ cup for 4), and a big squeeze of lime juice to pan. Simmer, stirring, until mixture has thickened and pork is cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Turn off heat. Season with salt and pepper to taste.

Divide pork filling and some slaw between buns. Divide pork sandwiches between plates. Serve with any remaining slaw and lime wedges on the side.